'''Force cloak''', also known as '''Force camouflage''', '''Force invisibility''', or '''Aura of insignifiance''', was a rarely seen [[The Force/Legends|Force]] [[Force power/Legends|talent]] involving the manipulation of light and sound waves to render a practitioner virtually invisible to the naked eye or making the Force user seem unworthy of notice. This technique was found mainly among members of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]] before the rise of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] and the destruction of the [[Jedi Temple/Legends|Jedi Temple]] on [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]]. Despite the loss of knowledge among the Jedi, the technique of cloaking oneself in the Force was perfected by the [[Disciples of Twilight]], a mysterious sect based on the [[Outer Rim Territories/Legends|Outer Rim]] [[Moon/Legends|moon]], [[Dyspeth]]. Another application was bending the perceptions of those around the Force user, so that they ignored the intruder.

Force cloak must not be confused with the inherent trait found in a [[Force void/Legends|Force Blank]] that produced the phenomenon of a ''void'' in the Force. Whereas the former was predominantly a talent or acquired skill among practitioners of the [[Light side of the Force/Legends|light side of the Force]], the latter was an inherent power found only among beings with natural leanings toward the [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side]], who gravitated or were naturally drawn to it.

==Description==
[[File:Force_Concealment.jpg|thumb|left|250px|A Force-user avoids detection by employing a cloaking technique.]]

The technique of cloaking oneself in [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] was one practiced by [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] individuals since the early days of the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]]. A rare ability, a Force-user would call upon their mastery of the Force to photo-kinetically bend light and sound waves around themselves, rendering them invisible to visual and audio detection. This skill tends to come to people as more of a natural talent, for it is extremely difficult to learn otherwise; thus, the reason the ability is rarely seen.<ref name="JvS:TEGTTF" /> While highly effective when practiced properly, maintaining such a cloak was extremely taxing and the concentration needed to make a convincing shroud could diminish the worth of employing the technique.<ref name="JvS:TEGTTF" />

Like all Force-based abilities, no single method existed to cloak oneself. An alternate version which did not involve a command over light and sound was an advanced form of [[Mind trick/Legends|mind trick]] or [[Mind trick/Legends#Force persuasion|Force persuasion]]. In this way, a user [[Alter Mind|affected the minds]] of those around them, removing all traces of their presence from the mind of observers and allowing them to move completely unnoticed while in plain sight. Unlike other methods of cloaking, droids and other nonliving individuals could not be fooled by a mind trick.<ref name="SECR" />

==History==
The origin of the cloaking technique is lost to history but study of the rare and seldom used ability can be seen in the teachings of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]] as early as the [[Great Sith War/Legends|Great Sith War]] in which it is defined as an [[Force power/Legends#Alter|''Alter'' ability]]. Accounts within the Order's [[Great Holocron/Legends|Great Holocron]] refer to the [[Cathar/Legends|Cathar]] [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] [[Juhani]], who was said to have possessed a natural talent for the skill.<ref name="JvS:TEGTTF" /> At the same time, [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]]-turned-[[Sith Lord/Legends|Sith Lord]] [[Kreia|Darth Traya]] favored the technique, believing that the perception of others was just another tool, a means by which to manipulate them. Through this technique, Traya and her alter-ego Kreia could move about friend and foe alike while cloaking herself.<ref name="KOTOR II">''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic II: The Sith Lords]]''</ref>

The Jedi Order maintained knowledge of the technique in the Great Holocron stored within the [[Jedi Archives/Legends|Archives]] of the [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] [[Jedi Temple/Legends|Jedi Temple]] for centuries. Jedi Master [[Tholme/Legends|Tholme]] was known to have passed the cloaking technique to his Padawan, [[Quinlan Vos/Legends|Quinlan Vos]], who would later impart the knowledge to [[Aayla Secura/Legends|Aayla Secura]].<ref name="JAS">''[[Jedi: Aayla Secura]]''</ref> The infamous Knight, and later [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Dark Lord of the Sith]], [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]] had learned the technique during the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]] and used it to successfully destroy the [[C-B3 cortosis battle droid/Legends|cortosis droid]] factory on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Metalorn/Legends|Metalorn]].<ref name="Star Wars: The New Droid Army">''[[Star Wars: The New Droid Army]]''</ref> In addition, as Darth Vader, he may have used the ability to remain invisible on [[Bespin/Legends|Bespin]] before fighting [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]], though this did not keep the boy from feeling his presence.

[[Darth Maul/Legends|Darth Maul]] had been trained to keep himself hidden from any quarry, so this technique would have been within his scope of abilities. At one time, he had successfully infiltrated the [[Kaldani Spires Residential Apartments]], where a [[Coruscant Security Force/Legends|police]] investigation was taking place.<ref name="Shadow Hunter">''[[Darth Maul: Shadow Hunter]]''</ref>

When the Jedi Order was disbanded by the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] at the end of the Clone Wars, the art lived on in several survivors. Padawan [[Maris Brood]] perfected the technique of cloaking herself to a deadly art, using it in conjunction with Force-enhanced [[Force speed/Legends|speed]] during her [[Battle of Felucia (Great Jedi Purge)|duel]] with the [[Sith assassin/Legends|Sith assassin]] [[Galen Marek|Starkiller]], though she was ultimately defeated. Jedi [[Jin-Lo Rayce]] taught the technique to members of his secret group known as the [[Agents of Ossus]] to evade detection by the prowling [[Inquisitorius/Legends|Inquisitorius]].<ref name="TFUCG">''[[The Force Unleashed Campaign Guide]]''</ref>

[[File:Disciple_of_Twilight.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A [[Disciples of Twilight|Disciple of Twilight]] cloaks himself with shadows.]]

While working with Mara Jade [[Rescue on the Chimaera|to rescue her employer]], Luke Skywalker used this power to make three men not realize he was stealing Imperial clothing.<ref name="Dark Force Rising">''[[Dark Force Rising]]''</ref> Members of the [[New Jedi Order|reformed Jedi Order]] would rediscover the Great Holocron and the teaching within, relearning the technique lost several decades before. During the early rebuilding process, Jedi [[Jaden Korr]] had some level of mastery in this skill, having the ability to distract others while he sneaked about.<ref name="Star Wars: Jedi Knight: Jedi Academy">''[[Star Wars: Jedi Knight: Jedi Academy]]''</ref>

Other groups aside from the Jedi had developed their own techniques that mirrored the Jedi's ability. Former [[Dathomir/Legends|Dathomiri]] [[Nightsisters/Legends|Nightsister]] [[Lomi Plo]] was skilled in the technique, using others doubts and fears to mask her from view during the [[Dark Nest Crisis]].<ref name="TUQ">''[[Dark Nest II: The Unseen Queen]]''</ref> Additionally, over the course of its existence the cult known as the [[Disciples of Twilight]] had created several variations of the technique to suit their needs. Calling one such technique '''Shadow Armor''', users of the ability would bend light and shadow around themselves to make their presence indistinguishable from the darkness.<ref name="LEC" />

